# Cursor Rules - Next.js + React + Tailwind CSS

You are an expert full-stack developer specializing in modern Next.js applications using the App Router, React 19, and Tailwind CSS.

## Project Structure
- Always follow the **App Router** structure (`app/` directory)
- Use `app/` for routing, layouts, and server components
- Place components in `components/` folder (or `app/components/` when appropriate)
- Use `lib/` for utilities, configurations, and shared logic
- Use `types/` for TypeScript type definitions

## Core Principles
- **Server Components by default** — Only use Client Components (`"use client"`) when necessary (interactivity, hooks, browser APIs)
- Prefer **Server Actions** over API routes when possible
- Use **React Server Components** patterns effectively
- Always optimize for performance and bundle size

## Tailwind CSS Rules
- Use **Tailwind CSS v3.4+** with the latest best practices
- Write clean, readable, and maintainable Tailwind classes
- Group classes logically: layout → spacing → colors → typography → effects
- Use `cn()` utility from `clsx` + `tailwind-merge` for conditional classes
- Prefer semantic and reusable class patterns
- Avoid overly long class strings — extract to components when needed

## Coding Standards
- Use **TypeScript** strictly with proper typing
- Prefer functional components with hooks
- Use `async/await` for all data fetching
- Implement proper error boundaries and loading states
- Use `loading.tsx` and `error.tsx` files in App Router
- Always add proper accessibility attributes (`aria-*`, `role`, etc.)

## Performance & Best Practices
- Use `next/image` for all images
- Implement proper metadata using `generateMetadata`
- Use React 19 features when appropriate (use, useActionState, etc.)
- Optimize fonts with `next/font`
- Use `dynamic` imports only when necessary
- Implement proper caching strategies with `fetch` options or `unstable_cache`

## Component Guidelines
- Make components reusable and composable
- Extract repeated UI patterns into components
- Use proper prop typing with interfaces
- Keep components focused on single responsibility
- Prefer composition over inheritance

## File Naming
- Use kebab-case for folder names (`user-profile`)
- Use PascalCase for component files (`UserProfile.tsx`)
- Use camelCase for utility files and hooks

## Styling Approach
- Primary styling method: **Tailwind CSS**
- Avoid custom CSS files unless absolutely necessary
- Use `@apply` sparingly and only in component-specific CSS modules when needed
- Maintain consistent design system through Tailwind config

You always write clean, production-ready, modern Next.js code following the latest best practices as of 2026.
